segments.text: When you consider his closeness with the congressman, the state senator, that one was shaky from time to time.
But nevertheless, when it comes down to the nitty-gritty, they were usually together, maybe after some arguments.
But the president, the congressman, the governor, the state representatives, nearly always,
I don't think we'll ever see a pattern like that again.
I mean, it was like a maroon umbrella.
And I understand that Mr.
Rudder and Jake Pickle, Congressman Austin, their friendship went back many years.
Yeah, way back to Austin.
And I think Mrs.
Rudder,
actually had as much or more contact with Jake because of social connections.
I think so.
I think more than President Rutter did, but they loved each other too.
It's nearly as if God had intervened.
There was no school.

you remember how excited we were about the first astronauts Teague was chairman of the house national aeronautics and space committee and we had who were those first ones John Glenn and Shepard maybe yeah anytime their name really went up in lights the next thing you know Teague had them here and

we were having our students were exposed to that kind of greatness way before anybody else ever dreamed of it and because it was because of the team rudder really and we had werner von braun uh that that was the most exciting thing to me in the jobs i've had here both as an assistant to rudder and williams and then and with com with commencement ceremonies
I could write a list of people that I it's been my good fortune just to be around a little bit just because of what those men amounted to their reputations.
One of the things I wish we had done started way way way back there would have been to have had all of the commencement speakers sign a program and put that in a file of some sort

it would make a good display because it really would have let's see Connolly on commencement speakers just there have been three that I know of that I can remember that were so good in their own style that they were invited twice John Connolly was one
Abner McCall was one.
President of Baylor.
Baylor.
And was it the writer from Houston that Dr. Williams loved so much?
Yes.
He was here twice.
Yes.
I can't think of his name, but he was so clever and so good.
Yes.
And he was a UT graduate, but
He could tell an Aggie story and then it would turn around and it would be a tea sipper story.
He was that good.
Back to that period of change, I have heard an anecdote that Senator Moore and President Rutter

on certain evenings ten o'clock or so would accidentally encounter each other in their cars in the parking lot of the campus theater and they would talk politics there without anyone else knowing about it have you ever heard that story no have not

I don't know whether it was true or not but the supposedly that because if I'm not mistaken part of those big discussions came when Senator Moore was running for reelection and Marion Pugh was running against him opposing

those changes and so president rudder could easily have been caught in the middle of that during that campaign i'm not saying that these things didn't happen i'm just saying that you didn't that i either had forgotten it and and time is a factor now
There are so many things that just barely come back to me now because it has been a long time.
Well yeah we're almost at 40 years.
Yes.
Let's go back to the start.
Did Mr.
Rudder give you any in any manner any guidelines as to what your responsibilities were and what the do's and don'ts of being his assistant?
uh there was never a job description and it was the kind of job where you served on a day-to-day basis once in a while there'd be a project that would extend out over time uh

An example would be he was greatly concerned when the Corps was made non-compulsory, he was greatly concerned about student life activities for non-Corps students that would stimulate the same spirit that participation in the Corps would do.
That's a very difficult challenge.
But that's the one thing that he asked me to work on that was really a serious project.
And to make a long story short, when I left his office, I became director of civilian student affairs.
And really his charge to me was find ways where we can generate spirit among those students so they feel strong about God and country and Texas A&M like the core students do.
And I did develop
the outline for the first residence hall program.
And he flinched.
He didn't like anything that cost money.
He was tight.
And he flinched when I gave him my first report, and it called for, it seemed like, oh, $65,000 to set up some residence halls on a trial basis with resident advisors on every floor.
And that was way more than that.

but he he went along and said we'll try it and now uh a lot of people don't know I was involved as much as I was in that program but that was that was my that was my answer to what he was shooting for uh your basic question is I would go into his office or he would come into mine

every morning and there would be two or three things on his mind that he wanted me to check out for him find out how the wind is blowing on this or that it might be a construction project there was just no pattern to it he'd say well so and so is saying this I hear see what you can find out so it was kind of like being a fireman though there were ongoing projects that
extended over time most of it was going in and finding out what was on his mind that day and I had what I call I had two manila folders one was a happy file and one was a mad file
And I could read him like a book after a while.
And I knew what to bring up and what not to bring up.
And if he was in a good mood, you could get nearly anything through.
If he was in a bad mood about something, you just better keep your mouth shut if there was any controversy involved with it.
When you began, describe the office staff.
Who else was there working in the president's office?
Geraldine Hott.
was the secretary.
She was good.
She'd been there for a while.
Nella Rowell came in.
I can't remember the sequence.
But she came in.
I was the only assistant at first.
That grew a little bit later.
As I recall, we had no graduate assistants.
I don't think we had any student employees.
Now, when I was William's assistant,

I did have an idea that we should come up with a title of staff assistant not assistant to and get people like Roger Miller and Gary Morrow and Kent Caperton to come in and work and see how these things work because my strategy was that these boys are going places and they're going to be high places
And if they have the insight that you can get only in this office, aren't we going to be better served in the years ahead?
Well, one became a state senator, one became a land commissioner, one became the state controller.
And, well, okay, that's on beyond rudder, though.
He wouldn't have gone for that because that would have cost thousands of dollars.
So it was a Spartan staff.
He had his assistant.
I had a secretary.
Who was your secretary?
I had Georgine Scafe, S-C-A-F-E, from Canada.
who could interpret letters from his friends in France.
That really pleased him.
She was as good as I've ever had.
And then I got... Well, I won't go into that one.
I had one that was just absolutely terrible.
But Georgene Scaife was the one most of the time, and she was just an absolute jewel.
Describe...
It was very small stuff.
Describe Ms. Hott and Nelda Rowell.
Describe them and their duties.
Ms. Hott did the routine and things like making out his schedule and taking the first look at the mail that came in and deciding where it should go for his eyes only.
And one of the things that I did, two things that I did for him that were pretty well developed as he tested me out, was that nearly every piece of mail that came in, I would draft his response.
And I knew him well enough after a period of time that I could pretty well guess what he wanted to say and how he wanted to say it.
And if I didn't quite hit it,
He would go ahead and sign the letter.
Come in.
That's all right.
Yeah, we're back.
Talking about the things that I was doing.

which relates back to an earlier question I would routinely do his correspondence which was considerable that would usually take at least half a day and a lot of it was stuff that you had to research you know finally well what is he saying this for and then try to just figure out and I could go to Geraldine Hott and say Jerry what do you think how would how do you think he'd feel on this and she could read him like a book she was very good and uh
The other thing that I did was write his speeches, which was in my estimation, it probably gave him the ideas that he didn't have time to research the little angles that I had time to do.
But I always dreaded to do a speech for him because if he read it and didn't have time to get it in his mind and do at least part of it extemporaneously, he was not good.
And on the other hand, he was as good as he could be off the cuff.

so what I would always hope for is that he would take time on the plane or the car to read through it get it in his mind and then do it his way and so I didn't like doing speeches for him because very often he would read them and he was very poor at that that's just as a young faculty member at that time I and my colleagues thought that he was not a good speech maker
but that he was good in what we called conversational speaking.
That's right.
And we would sometimes shake our heads and and snicker.
Then, on the other hand, I recall he is quite often indicating that he was aware that speech making was not his best talent.
So you're you would hope that you would provide him enough information
in a speech outline that he could put it into his own words.
Did he have any pet peeves or kind of things you realize about never, never in a speech?
No, not really.
He pretty well trusted me that I was not going to put together some things that just were nonsensical.
He was not big on, if he told jokes it would be extemporaneous and he could do that well.
But I would never write jokes into a speech.
He was pretty serious minded.
about how a speech should be constructed.
And that's kind of old school, which he was, really.
Prim and proper and the right things, thanks to the right people.
He was good at complimenting people for work that they contributed to a certain project.
When Nelda came along, Nelda, now Green, but then Rowell, she was kind of a staff assistant that worked in particular, I would say, those types of activities.
Let's say we were going to have a host a party or something of that sort for a group of people.
Nelda would usually be the one that would arrange for flowers and niceties and food service and things like that and I remember that both
Am I correct?
I can't think of exactly what year she came, but she worked with the President's wives incessantly.
She and Mrs. Williams later would spend months selecting the theme for a Christmas card, the official Christmas card.
She dealt with the women's kinds of things, that aspect of how a social event should go.
the arts and crafts of a president's office.
That's what I'm trying to say.
Nelda always seemed to me to be splendidly capable.
Do you have any idea who identified her?
How did the president's office find her?
She was a fairly young faculty wife at that time.
Didn't she start working for Bill Graff?
And or Wayne Hall, right in that little shop.
I don't know.
Yeah.
Okay, so that was.
So she was in his view, like when we were in the Koch building, his office, you know, the real nice office over here, and Bill Graff and then Dr. Hall, they were all right in that same little mix.
And Mr.
Rudder noticed attractive people.

and if you had a smart one that was an attractive person too you had a bird nest on the ground and she was that way always pleasant always smiled and I think he just lifted her from from that staff and I know she worked for Bill Graff and I think Wayne Hall too but she was right in there and she was right under he had to go right by her to get in and out of the building even
Now, when you went to work for Mr.
Rudder, the president's office was in the Koch building.
System building.
In the system building.
Then we moved to the Koch building.
Then moved to the Koch building.
And, of course, that had to do with the comings and goings of chancellors because the same offices were used.
The Koch building was designed by Mr. Volker from New Braunfels, Texas.
And he spent his entire life as a former student
praying to design a building on the A&M campus, and he did, and it was the worst designed building that's ever been built with an old flat roof.
The rooms don't connect properly.
Nothing is right about that building.
And one thing that was wrong about it was on the west side where my little office was,
next to the drill field, caught the western sun as it went down.

And I said to Mr. Rutter one time, back to his being real crisp about money, I said, do you think it would be possible for me to get some old cheap drapes to put in here to shield that sun out of here?
He said, Cooper, if we do that for you, everybody on campus will want drapes.
And he said, we can't afford it.
So I had a simple metal Venetian blind, and you'd come in there, you'd have to take your tie off, take your coat off, and it was intolerable, the heating system, the holes.
Then he came in there one August afternoon, about four o'clock, and it was about 82 degrees in there, and he said, my God, Cooper, he said, how can you work in this place?
I said, well, that's why I wanted those ACs.
Be quiet and get the damn things.
He said, I don't want to come in here and find you dead someday.
What was a, for Mr.
Rudder, describe a typical work day in the office.
What time did he get there?
He'd get there early if there was something real exciting underway.
I remember I always
feared coming in after eight and find him there and me come in after he did.
That was a lifelong fear that I had.

Williams was easy because he would spend two hours in his office at the house and he'd have all of his dictations done and he'd just give the tapes to whoever was out front when he came in and Rudder usually had
two feet of documents to sign when he came in and very often he would come in way before eight and get all of the reading and signatures out of the way.
Part of his hang-up was that he wanted to see in particular everything that dealt with money.
And he would not sign a document that had to do with a fiscal transaction without Tom Cherry or Clark Daigle's initials right there.
If it wasn't there, he would not sign it.
And so, he didn't go lightly with that stuff.
And when he signed his signature to something, you can bet your sweet life it's the way he wanted it or he wouldn't sign it.
Nothing just to get it out of the way.
He just wouldn't do that.

and so he held people highly accountable for uh for anything to do with policy changes money money transactions and things like that so he'd get in there early because he knew that around nine o'clock his day would be out of control and uh he couldn't say no to an old buddy that happened by that worked with the land commissioner that was from brady or you know he just he couldn't do that

So he would do the heavy work early and I would go in usually around 9 o'clock nearly every morning and sit with him and find out really what he wanted me to do that day or he would have things that he wanted to bounce off of me.
I'm not saying that I was that influential at all.
He just
When he wanted to get an average guy's reaction to something, he would ask me those questions.
And it always made me feel good when that door would open.
He'd knock at a little hall there at the system building, a little bitty office.
He'd knock and come in and sit on the desk and say, you know, this has really been on my mind.
And it made me feel real good when he would take me into his confidence because he was so busy that he didn't have time to do that whole lot.
There were days that we would be right next to each other and hardly ever see each other.
Lunches, were those usually working lunches or did he have a schedule that included a lot of social activity at lunch?
He loved to host lunches and very, very few of his lunches were at home.

he would have a lunch somewhere with someone and usually nearly always talk business did i tell you the story before about his daughter and the boy that she was in love with he was very strict with the girls they would they were the president's daughters they would not wear shorts even in the privacy of that house

that was not done and he kept Mrs. Rutter bless her heart on a very strict budget and most of the time she didn't have nearly all the help she needed when there was a function at the house he just expected her to do it he didn't want to spend money for that he'd buy the booze and the refreshments is always good but she had to she had to do most of it but Jane
fell in love with a nice-looking, big, old, tall boy that was headed into veterinary medicine.
And Mr. Rutter would not allow young men to come to the house, but she told this boy that on Thursday that nobody was going to be home but her, and she wanted to fix his lunch.
And they had worked this out.
He worked for buildings and grounds, and he worked as a gardener, working his way through school.
And that day, he was working in the president's rose garden.
They hauled him in on a dump truck.
You've seen them.
The whistle blew, which Dr. Williams stopped immediately when he got here, and the boy

threw his hoe down there in the president's yard and told the old guy with a khaki shirt buttoned at the collar he said y'all go on home for lunch he says I'm going to eat here walked in the front door of the president's home and the old man nearly had a heart attack his supervisor with physical plant he said I'm going to eat here and walked into the president's house and the guy could just see his job
flying out the window.
He had no idea about the boy.
I think it was Jane.
That was the funniest thing that I can recall about getting around the old man.
He was in four years under intense pressures.
I never saw him out of control of his temperament, never.
I could tell when he was really mad.
You could look at his eyes and he would turn ashy white and his eyes took on a laser beam, but he never raised his voice.
Jack Williams did.
I've seen him lose his temper once at me that really made me feel bad.
What would be the causes of Mr. Rutter's anger, frustration?
Somebody doing something that they knew was wrong and did it anyway, a policy matter.
He was very, very sensitive.
about the written word.
And if a battalion story came out, that would send him higher.
And you know of his, the DeFrank episode and all of that stuff.
But he was really sensitive about what people said, especially in print.
Not as much verbally,

as when somebody would write a story or be quoted as saying something and the kids picked up on that the students knew that and a lot of the misery that he went through is because they were doing it for fun and they took and one thing they did of course was take it out on the Bulldog Ranger and they would they had those little collar I mean little

blankets they'd strap on him and they'd put when when Mr. Rutter was promoted from brigadier to major general in the reserve you go from one star to two and that day Ranger came out with two gold stars on his on his blanket and then when he was having the big row with DeFrank
Ranger came by the office one day and he had on a blanket that said, I'm talking about a dog blanket, maroon.
And the big letter that says, I read bat editorials.
Now the students made the blankets.
They had one, evidently, that they just, whatever was on their mind that day, they would do it.
And I don't know who was behind all that, but I imagine Tommy DeFrank was part of it.
But if there was a big issue, Ranger would come out with some kind of an ornament or sign on that would poke fun at him.
One day I got a call from Ann Rudder in tears on the phone.
It was a Sunday afternoon.
And she says, Edwin, I think Ranger's drowned.
I said, come on.
Dogs don't drown.
All dogs can swim.
She said, well, he jumped out of our boat.
He went down, and he hadn't come out.
So wherever I was, I went out to Carter Creek.
And that dog had jumped out of that boat and went down like a sack of concrete to the bottom and drowned.

and she says how are we going to find him I said well let me see I found a fishing pole I said where do you think it was and we were out in the boat and I prodded around and finally I felt it I said he's right here and I don't know whether I went down or I guess I did.
